# Framework Strategy Invariants

## Quality invariants

- Zero domain imports. The framework never imports from consumer tools.
- Interface-driven design. Consumers implement framework interfaces; the framework provides orchestration.
- Deterministic for the same inputs. Seed ordering where needed.
- Progressive disclosure (Papert Paradigm). Basic usage requires zero configuration; advanced features are opt-in.
- Every component follows low floor / high ceiling / wide walls.
- All configuration and pipeline definitions use git-diffable text formats.

## Design invariants

- **DSL-first.** Pipelines are declared in YAML and compiled to executable graphs.
- **Single-method interfaces.** Prefer narrow interfaces that compose via adapters and chains.
- **Functional options.** Constructor tuning via `WithX` pattern, not mandatory parameters.
- **Pass-through defaults.** Unknown inputs return unchanged, never panic.
- **Observability built-in.** Every graph walk emits events that observers can capture. Zero-config logging via `LogObserver`.

## BYO Architecture

The framework owns contract shapes, never implementations. Seven named principles enforce this boundary:

| Principle | Meaning | Framework provides | Consumer provides |
|---|---|---|---|
| **BYOB** (Bring Your Own Bots) | LLM/agent backends are external | `Dispatcher` interface, `MuxDispatcher`, `FileDispatcher` | OpenAI adapter, Anthropic SDK, custom agent |
| **BYOA** (Bring Your Own Auth) | Credentials never touch the framework | Clean injection points on dispatchers and sources | Vault, OIDC, mTLS, service accounts |
| **BYOS** (Bring Your Own Storage) | Persistence is an interface, not a dependency | `curate.Store`, `Hook`, in-memory `WalkerState` | Postgres, S3, Redis, etcd |
| **BYOD** (Bring Your Own Domain) | Domain logic lives in consumers | `Node`, `Walker`, `Transformer`, `Hook` interfaces | Domain nodes, walkers, hooks, YAML pipelines |
| **BYOR** (Bring Your Own Rules) | Routing logic and decision thresholds are consumer-defined | `when:` expression engine, `vars:` config, `EdgeFactory` | Domain-specific routing rules, custom evaluators |
| **BYO-Data** (Bring Your Own Datasets) | Calibration data and ground truth are consumer-curated | `curate` package, Three CLIs pattern | Domain ground truth, calibration datasets |
| **BYOI** (Bring Your Own Infrastructure) | Topology-agnostic execution | `origami run` CLI, `Dispatcher` abstraction | Cursor subagents, Linux+CLI, Docker, K8s |

Every BYO interface ships at least one trivial PoC-ready implementation ("Batteries for PoC"). See `strategy/origami-vision.mdc` for the full articulation.

## Stability invariants

- Maintain backward compatibility for exported interfaces (Node, Edge, Graph, Walker, Artifact, Extractor).
- New features add optional YAML keys with sensible defaults (progressive disclosure).
- Breaking changes require a major version bump.
- Tests pass with `-race` flag. No shared mutable state without synchronization.
